column10:
Status 
"In Prep" -  preparing buoy for deployment
"Active" - at sea and we plan to recover
"Lost" - at sea but unlikely we can recover
“Sunk” - only recovered partial buoy, assumed dead, sunk, and highly unlikely to recover
“Complete” -  buoy recovered and data is in house "Unusable" - buoy recovered but data is unusable
column28: Array_name (Array letter + 2 digit version number_Hydrophone model numbers)
column37: Data_Start_UTC (defined once data is recovered by scanning LTSA)
column38: Data_End_UTC (defined once data is recovered by scanning LTSA)
column68: Notes
Location 1 on map from Jeff. Head piece flooded and terminals between the spots and the batteries are fried. Wav files have knocking below 3kHz from trailing buoy hitting the PIFSC buoy
Location 3 on map from Jeff. Head piece flooded. The yellow collar was damaged from moving up and down the spar. The hose clamp slipped way down the buoy
Location A on map from Jeff. Head piece flooded and one spot stopped talking
Location 2 on map from Jeff. Head piece flooded and Spot R shorted out.
Location B on map from Jeff. Head piece flooded
Location 5 on map from Jeff. Recorder stopped recording after the first SD card? I will bench test it and see if I can figure out what happened
Location D on map from Jeff
Location 7 on map from Jeff
Location 6 on map from Jeff. Bungee was very stretched upon recovery. Recovered near fin whale (<2nm)
Deployed in Eureka WEA, Testing modified PIFSC buoy (10lbs drilled to the spar)

Deployed in Eureka WEA, Testing modified PIFSC buoy (10lbs drilled to the spar). Spot AD was not always reporting it's location consistently but then later in the day all of the locations would show up at once on the website. Recovered without leaking in head piece, must be a Spot interface issue
Deployed in Eureka WEA with Ogger. Retrieval looks good
Location 8 on map from Jeff. Ogger deployed. Retrieved next to orca following a fin whale
Location H on map from Jeff. PIFSC buoy
Location G on map from Jeff. Pole buoy
Location 9 on map from Jeff. Recovered in rough conditions, common dolphins near by
Location 10 on map from Jeff. PIFSC buoy. Lots of fin whales in the vacinity upon retrieval
Location J on map from Jeff. Pole buoy. Common dolphins nearby during recovery, night recovery
Location 14 on map from Jeff. Pole buoy. Sei whale sighted shortly after recovery, OPPS deployed
Location K on map from Jeff. Pole buoy. Night recovery. ~6 minute gap at 11-07-24 18:24:03, recorder switched to a second SD card
Location 16 on map from Jeff. Pole buoy. Night recovery
Location L on map from Jeff. Pole buoy. Night deployment
Location N on map from Jeff. Pole buoy

Location 18 on map from Jeff. Pole buoy. Shortly after retrieving DASBR 27, we went back on effort and sighted a group of 3 sei whales. These are sighting #1237. They were sighted approx 5 miles from the DASBR retrieval location, within about 45 min of getting the DASBR on board. 365 sec (0.1 hrs) gap after 11/28/2024 19:42:03, recorder switched to a second SD card
Location M on map from Jeff. Pole buoy
